<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is JSON validation?", answer: "JSON validation checks whether a string conforms to the JSON specification (RFC 8259). A valid JSON document must use double-quoted strings, have no trailing commas, no comments, and properly matched brackets and braces. The validator parses your input and reports whether it is well-formed or identifies the specific syntax error and its location." },
  { question: "Why should I validate JSON?", answer: "Validating JSON before using it prevents runtime errors in your applications. APIs, configuration files, and data imports all depend on well-formed JSON. A single missing comma or mismatched bracket can cause an entire request to fail. Validating early catches these issues before they reach production systems." },
  { question: "What are common JSON errors?", answer: "The most common JSON errors include trailing commas after the last item in an array or object, single quotes instead of double quotes for strings, unquoted property keys, missing commas between items, comments (which are not allowed in standard JSON), and mismatched or missing closing brackets and braces." },
  { question: "Can JSON have comments?", answer: "No, the JSON specification does not allow comments. This is one of the most common sources of validation errors. If you need comments in configuration files, consider using JSONC (JSON with Comments) or YAML instead. Some parsers support a non-standard comment extension, but standard JSON validators will reject them." },
  { question: "What is the maximum size of a JSON document?", answer: "The JSON specification does not define a maximum size. In practice, limits depend on the parser and environment. Browsers typically handle JSON documents up to several hundred megabytes. Server-side parsers may have configurable limits. This online tool works well with JSON up to a few megabytes in size." }
]) %>

